CONCEPTS = [
 {"title":"Looking out is looking back","body":"Light takes time to travel, so the farther away something is, the older the light we see. Looking deep into space is also looking deep into the past, all the way back toward the early universe.","src":"nasa"},
 {"title":"Gravity rules everything","body":"From a falling apple to the orbits of planets and the shape of galaxies, one gentle force shapes it all. The more mass an object has, the stronger its pull, and the closer you are, the stronger it feels.","src":"nasa"},
 {"title":"We are made of star stuff","body":"The atoms in your body, the iron in your blood and the oxygen you breathe were forged inside stars and scattered by their deaths. Every person is built from the ashes of ancient stars.","src":"esahubble"},
 {"title":"The universe is mostly empty","body":"Space is vast and the objects in it are tiny by comparison. Even the busy-looking asteroid belt is so spread out that spacecraft pass through it with ease.","src":"nasaplanets"},
 {"title":"Stars are born, live and die","body":"Stars form in clouds of gas, shine for millions or billions of years, then end as fading embers or violent explosions. Their endings seed space with the material for new stars and worlds.","src":"esahubble"},
 {"title":"Our place is humble","body":"Earth is one small world circling an ordinary star, in one of hundreds of billions of galaxies. Astronomy gently reminds us how vast the universe is and how much we still have to learn.","src":"iau"},
 {"title":"The sky is a clock and a map","body":"For thousands of years people have used the Sun, Moon and stars to mark time, find direction and plan the seasons. The motions of the sky are steady and predictable.","src":"nasa"},
 {"title":"The universe is expanding","body":"Distant galaxies are racing away from us, and the farther they are, the faster they recede. Space itself is stretching, carrying the galaxies apart like raisins in rising dough.","src":"esahubble"},
 {"title":"Science changes with evidence","body":"When new discoveries arrive, science updates its ideas, even cherished ones. Pluto's move from planet to dwarf planet shows how definitions sharpen as we learn more.","src":"iau"},
 {"title":"Anyone can explore the sky","body":"Astronomy begins with simply looking up. With patient eyes, a star map, or a pair of binoculars, anyone can find planets, clusters and the band of the Milky Way.","src":"nasa"},
]

